A wife who is no longer valued due to infertility or poor performance in household work may be susceptible to domestic violence and forced divorce. In addition, husbands often deny women child maintenance when they are divorced.

Divorced women also face biases in labor market and are often forced to migrate from their husband’s village. Although the government has taken initiatives to improve women’s access to education and skills training, human rights organizations continue to work with the government, social institutions, and civil organizations to increase women of Bangladesh’s confidence and self-reliance. Women Rising, the project funded by the US Philanthropy Fund and the German Development Bank, which works for social justice and economic empowerment of poor women of Bangladeshis working towns. Since the project began in 2003, it has specially targeted newly migrated women who are especially vulnerable and independent groups have become self-sufficient and strong partners for development. Global mechanisms of accountability and the women of Bangladesh are now increasingly participating in local government meetings and influencing local government.
